title: NASA, Oxford Discover Warmer Uranus Than Once Thought
description: KEY POINTS For millennia, astronomers thought Uranus was no more than a distant star. It wasn’t until the late 18th century that Uranus was universally accepted as a planet. To this day, the ringed, blue world subverts scientists’ expectations, but new NASA research helps puzzle out some of the world’s mystique.  Uranus is unlike any […]

title: NASA’s X-59 Quiet Supersonic Aircraft Begins Taxi Tests
description: NASA/Jacob Shaw NASA’s X-59 quiet supersonic research aircraft has officially begun taxi tests, marking the first time this one-of-a-kind experimental aircraft has moved under its own power. NASA test pilot Nils Larson and the X-59 team, made up of NASA and contractor Lockheed Martin personnel, completed the aircraft’s first low-speed taxi test at U.S. Air […]
author: Dede Dinius

title: Simple device can produce water, oxygen and fuel from lunar soil
description: Using samples collected by the Chinese Chang’e 5 mission, researchers have discovered a new way to release water from lunar regolith and process the carbon dioxide breathed out by astronauts

title: Water might be even more important for alien life than we thought
description: Without enough liquid water on the surface, a planet's atmosphere can become choked with carbon dioxide, raising temperatures to a level beyond what is survivable for all known life

title: Two black holes collide, lab-grown organs, world’s first climate visa – podcast
description: Madeleine Finlay is joined by Ian Sample to discuss three intriguing science and environment stories. From a breakthrough in the quest to create organs in the lab to a world-first climate visa that will see citizens relocate from the island of Tuvalu to Australia, plus what happens when two massive black holes collideScientists detect biggest ever merger of two massive black holesA climate crisis, a ballot, and a chance at a new life in Australia Continue reading...
author: Presented by Madeleine Finlay with Ian Sample, produced by Tom Glasser, sound design by Ross Burns, executive producer Ellie Bury

title: Astronomers see formation of new solar system around distant sun for first time
description: Seeds of rocky planets forming in gas around star Hops-315 is called glimpse of ‘time zero’, when new worlds start to gelAstronomers have discovered the earliest seeds of rocky planets forming in the gas around a baby sun-like star, providing a precious peek into the dawn of our own solar system.It’s an unprecedented snapshot of “time zero”, scientists reported on Wednesday, when new worlds begin to gel. author: Associated Press

title: What's the deal with Lex Luthor's pocket universe in James Gunn's 'Superman'?
description: Superman is full of awesome sci-fi elements, but the most fascinating one might be Lex Luthor's pocket dimension. How does that even work?
author: Fran Ruiz

title: Scientists extracted water and oxygen from moon dust using sunlight. Could it work on the lunar surface?
description: Soil excavated from the moon could be used to produce oxygen and methane, which could be used by lunar settlers for breathing and for rocket fuel.
author: Keith Cooper
